\u00e9ris]]|FRA}} || France || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 2h 19' 31\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |37\n| {{flagathlete|[[Nello Lauredi]]|FRA}} || France || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 2h 22' 05\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |38\n| {{flagathlete|[[Maurice Kallert]]|FRA}} || South-East || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 2h 23' 29\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |39\n| {{flagathlete|[[Roger Creton]]|FRA}} || West || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 2h 24' 28\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |40\n| {{flagathlete|[[Ahmed Kebaili]]|FRA}} || North Africa || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 2h 27' 17\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |41\n| {{flagathlete|[[Georges Aeschlimann]]|SUI}} || Switzerland || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 2h 34' 05\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |42\n| {{flagathlete|[[Serge Blusson]]|FRA}} || Paris || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 2h 38' 14\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |43\n| {{flagathlete|[[Emilio Croci-Torti]]|SUI}} || Switzerland || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 2h 38' 40\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |44\n| {{flagathlete|[[Robert Bonnaventure]]|FRA}} || West || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 2h 50' 43\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |45\n| {{flagathlete|[[No\u00ebl Lajoie]]|FRA}} || Centre/South-West || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 2h 52' 05\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |46\n| {{flagathlete|[[Robert Desbats]]|FRA}} || France || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 2h 56' 27\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |47\n| {{flagathlete|[[Jos\u00e9 Beyaert]]|FRA}} || Paris || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 3h 12' 07\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |48\n| {{flagathlete|[[\u00c9mile Baffert]]|FRA}} || France || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 3h 22' 51\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |49\n| {{flagathlete|[[Gilbert Bauvin]]|FRA}} || \u00cele-de-France/North-East || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 3h 35' 39\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |50\n| {{flagathlete|[[Gottfried Weilenmann (cyclist, born 1920)|Gottfried Weilenmann]]|SUI}} || Switzerland || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 3h 57' 50\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |51\n| {{flagathlete|[[Fritz Zbinden]]|SUI}} || Switzerland || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 4h 06' 47\"\n|}\n\n{{columns-start}}\n\n===Mountains classification===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Final mountains classification (1\u201310)<ref>{{cite news|title=K\u00fcbler schudde concurrent Ockers in tijdrace los|trans-title=K\u00fcbler shook off competitor Ockers in time race|url=https://www.delpher.nl/nl/kranten/view?coll=ddd&identifier=ddd:011155433:mpeg21:p003|work=[[De Gooi- en Eemlander]]|date=7 August 1950|page=3|language=Dutch|via=[[Delpher]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Ferdi K\u00fcbler loopt zes minuten uit op Ockers, in fraaie tijdrace|trans-title=Ferdi K\u00fcbler ends six minutes on Ockers in a nice time race|url=https://www.delpher.nl/nl/kranten/view?coll=ddd&identifier=ddd:010852468:mpeg21:p004|work=[[De Waarheid]]|date=7 August 1950|page=4|language=Dutch|via=[[Delpher]]}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Rank!! scope=\"col\" | Rider!! scope=\"col\" | Team!! scope=\"col\" | Points\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |1\n| {{flagathlete|[[Louison Bobet]]|FRA}} || France || style=\"text-align:right;\" |   58\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |2\n| {{flagathlete|[[Stan Ockers]]|BEL}} || Belgium || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 42\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |3\n| {{flagathlete|[[Jean Robic]]|FRA}} || West || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 41\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |4\n| {{flagathlete|[[Ferdinand K\u00fcbler]]|SUI}} || Switzerland || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 39\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |5\n| {{flagathlete|[[Kl\u00e9ber Piot]]|FRA}} || \u00cele-de-France/North-East || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 36\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |6\n| {{flagathlete|[[Rapha\u00ebl G\u00e9miniani]]|FRA}} || France || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 33\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |7\n| {{flagathlete|[[Andr\u00e9 Brul\u00e9 (cyclist)|Andr\u00e9 Brul\u00e9]]|FRA}} || \u00cele-de-France/North-East || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 19\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |8\n| {{flagathlete|[[Georges Meunier]]|FRA}} || Centre/South-West || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 14\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |9\n| {{flagathlete|[[Raymond Impanis]]|BEL}} || Belgium || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 12\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |10\n| {{flagathlete|[[Pierre Brambilla]]|FRA}} || South-East || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 10\n|}\n\n{{column}}\n\n===Team classification===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Final team classification<ref>{{cite news|url=http://krantenarchief.concentra.be/vw/article.do?code=GVA&date=19500808&id=GVA-19500808-01008005|title=Belgi\u00eb wint het landenklassement|trans-title=Belgium wins the country ranking|language=Dutch|work=[[Gazet van Antwerpen]]|date=8 August 1950|page=8|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191004132952/http://krantenarchief.concentra.be/vw/article.do?code=GVA&date=19500808&id=GVA-19500808-01008005|archive-date=4 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Rank!! scope=\"col\" | Team!! scope=\"col\" | Time\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |1\n| Belgium || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 438h 54' 21\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |2\n| France || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 38' 05\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |3\n| Luxembourg || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 41' 05\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |4\n| \u00cele-de-France/North-East || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 1h 12' 28\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |5\n| South-East || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 1h 32' 22\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |6\n| Centre/South-West || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 1h 53' 16\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |7\n| Belgium Aiglons || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 2h 01' 34\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |8\n| Switzerland || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 3h 09' 12\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |9\n| West || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 3h 28' 56\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |10\n| Paris || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 5h 51' 48\"\n|}\n\n{{columns-end}}\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe French-Algerian cyclist Zaaf, who fell out in the thirteenth stage after riding into the wrong direction, became famous, and got to ride in many [[criterium]]s, until he left two years later to Algeria.<ref name=\"cwszaaf\"/> K\u00fcbler did not enter the next three Tours de France, but when he returned in [[1954 Tour de France|1954]], he finished in second place, and won the green jersey for the [[points classification in the Tour de France|points classification]].\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book|last=Amels|first=Wim|title=De geschiedenis van de Tour de France 1903\u20131984|location=Valkenswaard, Netherlands|publisher=Sport-Express|year=1984|language=Dutch|isbn=978-90-70763-05-3|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Jacques|last=Augendre|author-link=Jacques Augendre|url=http://netstorage.lequipe.fr/ASO/cyclisme/le-tour/2016/histoire/TDF16_GH_Interactif-PROD.pdf|title=Guide historique|trans-title=Historical guide|year=2016|language=French|access-date=27 October 2016|format=PDF|work=[[Tour de France]]|location=Paris|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817121602/http://netstorage.lequipe.fr/ASO/cyclisme/le-tour/2016/histoire/TDF16_GH_Interactif-PROD.pdf|archive-date=17 August 2016|url-status=live|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=McGann|first1=Bill|last2=McGann|first2=Carol|title=The Story of the Tour de France: 1903\u20131964|volume=1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jxq20JskqMUC|publisher=Dog Ear Publishing|location=Indianapolis, IN|year=2006|isbn=978-1-59858-180-5|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Nauright|first1=John|last2=Parrish|first2=Charles|title=Sports Around the World: History, Culture, and Practice|volume=2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IkLYDgTnMxEC|year=2012|publisher=[[ABC-CLIO]]|location=Santa Barbara, CA|isbn=978-1-59884-300-2|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|title=The Tour de France: A Cultural History|last=Thompson|first=Christopher S.|year=2006|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=0-520-24760-4|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=M-vUF6Y_4RUC}}\n* {{cite book|last=Whittle|first=Jeremy|title=Le Tour: A Century of the Tour de France|location=Osceola, WI|publisher=MBI Publishing Company|year=2003|url=https://archive.org/details/letourcenturyoft0000whit|url-access=registration|isbn=978-0-7603-1671-9}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category-inline|Tour de France 1950|1950 Tour de France}}\n\n{{Cycling stage recaps|1950 Tour de France|1|11|12|22}}\n{{Tour de France}}\n{{1950 Challenge Desgrange-Colombo}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1950 Tour De France}}\n[[Category:1950 Tour de France| ]]\n[[Category:1950 in French sport|Tour De France, 1950]]\n[[Category:Tour de France by year]]\n[[Category:1950 in road cycling]]\n[[Category:July 1950 sports events|Tour de France]]\n[[Category:August 1950 sports events|Tour de France]]\n[[Category:1950 Challenge Desgrange-Colombo|Tour de France]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox cycling race report\n| name               = 1950 Tour de France\n| image              = Route of the 1950 Tour de France.png\n| image_caption      = Route of the 1950 Tour de France followed counterclockwise, starting and finishing in Paris\n| image_alt          =\n| image_size         = 350px\n| date               = 13 July \u2013 7 August\n| stages             = 22\n| distance           = 4773\n| unit               = km\n| time               = 145h 36' 56\"\n| first              = [[Ferdinand K\u00fcbler]]\n| first_nat          = SUI\n| first_color        = yellow\n| first_team         = Switzerland\n| second             = [[Stan Ockers]]\n| second_nat         = BEL\n| second_team        = Belgium\n| third              = [[Louison Bobet]]\n| third_nat          = FRA\n| third_team         = France\n| team               = Belgium\n| mountains          = [[Louison Bobet]]\n| mountains_nat      = FRA\n| mountains_team     = France\n| previous           = [[1949 Tour de France|1949]]\n| next               = [[1951 Tour de France|1951]]\n}}\nThe '''1950 Tour de France''' was the 37th edition of the [[Tour de France]], taking place from 13 July to 7 August. It consisted of 22 stages over {{convert|4773|km|0|abbr=on}}.\n\nGino Bartali, captain of the Italian team, threatened and assaulted by some French supporters accusing him to have caused Jean Robic's fall on the Col d'Aspin, retired after winning the 12th stage from Pau to Saint-Gaudens and left the race together with all the other Italian riders (including Fiorenzo Magni, who was wearing the yellow jersey).{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=41}} The lead transferred to Swiss cyclist [[Ferdinand K\u00fcbler]], who was able to keep the lead until the end of the race. K\u00fcbler became the first Swiss winner of the Tour de France.\n\nThe mountains classification was won by [[Louison Bobet]], while the Belgian team won the team classification.\n\nAlgerian-French cyclist Abdel-Kader Zaaf became famous in this Tour de France by being so disoriented that he rode in the wrong direction.\n\n==Changes from the previous Tour==\nThe \"interest\" for the yellow jersey (the prize money for the leader of the general classification after each stage) was increased to 100.000 French Francs.{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=41}}\nIn 1949, the French TV had reported every evening about the Tour de France, and in 1950, live coverage of every stage was given.<ref>Thompson, p.46</ref>\nThe time cut-offs, the maximum time a cyclist was allowed to finish a stage, was reduced.<ref name=\"letour.fr\"/>\n\nIn the previous years, the Tour de France had been decided in the mountains. The organisation wanted the other aspects of the race to be more important, so some mountains were not visited in 1950, and the time bonification for cyclists that reached mountain tops first was reduced. from 1 minute in 1949 to 40 seconds in 1950.<ref name=\"elm\">{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca-paginas.mundodeportivo.com/EMD02/HEM/1950/07/14/MD19500714-001.pdf|title=La XXXVII Vuelta a Francia|language=Spanish|date=14 July 1950|work=[[Mundo Deportivo]]|page=1|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120731200306/http://hemeroteca-paginas.mundodeportivo.com/EMD02/HEM/1950/07/14/MD19500714-001.pdf|archive-date=31 July 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe riders had sometimes been helped by team assistants who directly assisted the riders by pushing them from within the team cars, under the pretence of supplying them with a drink. In 1950, the Tour organisation paid extra care for this, and penalised the cyclists if it happened.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.archiefleeuwardercourant.nl/site/article.do?code=LC&date=19500713&id=LC-19500713-5012|title=Tour de France 1950|publisher=Leeuwarder Courant|date=13 July 1950|accessdate=3 December 2009|language=Dutch}}</ref>\n\nThe prize for winning a stage was increased from 30.000 French Francs to 50.000 French Francs.<ref name=\"elm\"/>\n\n==Teams==\n{{main list|List of teams and cyclists in the 1950 Tour de France}}\n\n[[File:Dutch team at the start in Paris, 1950 Tour de France.jpg|thumb|The Dutch team at the start of the race in [[Paris]]]]\nAs was the custom since the [[1930 Tour de France]], the 1950 Tour de France was contested by national and regional teams. The three major cycling countries in 1950, Italy, Belgium and France, each sent a team of 10 cyclists. Other countries sent teams of 6 cyclists: Switzerland, Luxembourg and the Netherlands. Italy and Belgium also sent two extra teams of young riders of 6 cyclists each.\nThe French regional cyclists were divided into five teams of 10 cyclists: Paris, \u00cele-de-France/North-East, West, Centre/South-West and South-East. Originally, the plan was to have one extra international team of six cyclists with Spanish cyclists,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.archiefleeuwardercourant.nl/site/article.do?code=LC&date=19491216&id=LC-19491216-3005|title=De Tour de France in 1950|publisher=Leeuwarder Courant|date=13 July 1950|accessdate=3 December 2009|language=Dutch}}</ref> but this extra team became a North African team, with Moroccan and Algerian cyclists; at the time, portions of Morocco were [[French protectorate in Morocco|a French protectorate]], and Alergia was [[French Algeria|an integral part of France]]. This was the first African team to compete in the Tour de France.<ref name=\"CN AF\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/features/retro-the-1950-tour-de-france-and-the-forgotten-first-african-team |title=Retro: The 1950 Tour de France and the forgotten first African team |author=Barry Ryan |date=2 July 2015 |work=Cycling News|publisher= Immediate Media Company |accessdate=2 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150702150455/http://www.cyclingnews.com/features/retro-the-1950-tour-de-france-and-the-forgotten-first-african-team|archive-date=2 July 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Altogether this made 116 cyclists.<ref name=\"mdc1950\"/>\n\nThere were 60 French cyclists (of which 2 French-Moroccan and 4 French-Algerian), 22 Italian, 16 Belgian, 6 Dutch, 6 Luxembourg and 6 Swiss cyclists.<ref name=\"tgv\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tour-giro-vuelta.net|title=Tour-Giro-Vuelta|work=www.tour-giro-vuelta.net|accessdate=2 December 2009}}</ref> On the first day of the race, before the Tour had started, French cyclist [[Charles Coste]] was replaced by [[Paul Giguet]].<ref name=\"elm\"/>\n\nThe teams entering the race were:\n\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* Italy\n* Belgium\n* France\n* Switzerland\n* Luxembourg\n* Netherlands\n* Italy Cadets\n* Belgium Aiglons\n* Paris\n* \u00cele-de-France/North-East\n* West\n* Centre/South-West\n* South-East\n* North Africa\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Pre-race favourites==\nThe winner of the previous Tour de France, [[Fausto Coppi]], was injured during the [[1950 Giro d'Italia]], so he could not defend his title.{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=41}} Still the Italians were favourites, especially [[Gino Bartali]], who had come second in the 1950 Giro d'Italia behind [[Hugo Koblet]], who did not enter the 1950 Tour de France. Other candidates for the victory were Bobet, K\u00fcbler, Ockers and Geminiani.{{sfn|Amels|1984|pp=61\u201362}} Two days before the Tour started, the organisation held a poll amongst 25 journalists, who each gave their eight favourites for the victory. Bartali was on the most lists, 23. Robic was written on 20 lists, Lauredi on 19, Bobet and Goldschmidt on 17.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://archiefeemland.courant.nu/index.php?page=1&mod=krantresultaat&q=%22jacques+goddet%22&datering=&krant=&qt=paragraaf&pagina=&sort=datum+asc,krant+asc,pagina+asc&doc=1&p=3&paragraaf=27&y=142 |title=Gino Bartali, de grote favoriet voor de Tour |publisher=Archief Eemland |work=Dagblad voor Amersfoort |date=11 July 1950 |page=3 |accessdate=13 September 2010 |language=Dutch |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131104180142/http://archiefeemland.courant.nu/index.php?page=1&mod=krantresultaat&q=%22jacques%2Bgoddet%22&datering=&krant=&qt=paragraaf&pagina=&sort=datum%2Basc%2Ckrant%2Basc%2Cpagina%2Basc&doc=1&p=3&paragraaf=27&y=142 |archive-date=4 November 2013 |df= }}</ref>\n\n==Route and stages==\n\nThe 1950 Tour de France started on 13 July, and had four rest days, in Dinard, Pau, Nice and Saint-\u00c9tienne.{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=41}} The route had been revealed in January 1950.<ref name=\"CDS Rv\">{{cite web|url=http://dlib.coninet.it/bookreader.php?&c=1&f=7804&p=1#page/3/mode/1up|title=Il Tour de France \u00e9 pronto|work=Corriere dello Sport|date=24 January 1950|page=3|accessdate=7 July 2013|language=Italian|trans-title=The Tour de France is ready|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190928191019/http://dlib.coninet.it/bookreader.php?&c=1&f=7804&p=1#page/1/mode/2up|archivedate=28 September 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> The [[List of highest points reached in the Tour de France|highest point of elevation in the race]] was {{convert|2360|m|ft|abbr=on}} at the summit of the [[Col d'Izoard]] mountain pass on stage 18.{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=178}}<ref>{{cite news|title=Tour de France beheerst Parijs|trans-title=Tour de France masters Paris|url=https://resolver.kb.nl/resolve?urn=ABCDDD:010834996:mpeg21:p005|work=[[Het Parool]]|date=12 July 1950|page=5|language=Dutch|via=[[Delpher]]}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Stage characteristics and winners<ref name=\"mdc1950\">{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1947_1977/tdf1950.php|publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme|title=37\u00e8me Tour de France 1950|language=French|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120901150902/http://www.memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1947_1977/tdf1950.php|archive-date=1 September 2012|access-date=26 September 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=41}}<ref name=\"topten\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cvccbike.com/tour/top_ten.html#1950 |title=Tour de France GC top ten |author=Arian Zwegers |publisher=CVCC |accessdate=3 December 2009 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/5hQnRPAvL?url=http://www.cvccbike.com/tour/top_ten.html |archive-date=10 June 2009 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Stage\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | Course\n! scope=\"col\" | Distance\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\" | Type\n! scope=\"col\" | Winner\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |1\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 13 July\n| [[Paris]] to [[Metz]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|307|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage ||{{flagathlete|[[Jean Goldschmit]]|LUX}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |2\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 14 July\n| [[Metz]] to [[Li\u00e8ge]] (Belgium)|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|241|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage ||{{flagathlete|[[Adolfo Leoni]]|ITA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |3\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 15 July\n| [[Li\u00e8ge]] (Belgium) to [[Lille]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|232.5|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage ||{{flagathlete|[[Alfredo Pasotti]]|ITA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |4\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 16 July\n| [[Lille]] to [[Rouen]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" 