day\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |17\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 1 August\n| [[Nice]] to [[Gap, Hautes-Alpes|Gap]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|229|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s) ||{{flagathlete|[[Rapha\u00ebl G\u00e9miniani]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |18\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 2 August\n| [[Gap, Hautes-Alpes|Gap]] to [[Brian\u00e7on]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|165|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s) ||{{flagathlete|[[Louison Bobet]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |19\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 3 August\n| [[Brian\u00e7on]] to [[Saint-\u00c9tienne]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|291 |km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s) ||{{flagathlete|[[Rapha\u00ebl G\u00e9miniani]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 4 August\n| colspan=\"2\" | [[Saint-\u00c9tienne]]\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" | Rest day\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |20\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 5 August\n| [[Saint-\u00c9tienne]] to [[Lyon]]||{{convert|98|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Mountain Time Trial Stage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || [[Individual time trial|Mountain time trial]]||{{flagathlete|[[Ferdinand K\u00fcbler]]|SUI}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |21\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 6 August\n| [[Lyon]] to [[Dijon]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|233|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage ||{{flagathlete|[[Gino Sciardis]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |22\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 7 August\n| [[Dijon]] to [[Paris]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|314|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage ||{{flagathlete|[[\u00c9mile Baffert]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"| Total\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center\"| {{convert|4773|km|0|abbr=on}}{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=109}}\n|}\n{{Reflist|group=\"notes\"}}\n\n==Race overview==\nThe start of the 1950 Tour de France was given on 13 July by [[Orson Welles]].{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=41}} Things started well for the Italian team, as they won five of the first ten stages,<ref name=\"veloarchive\">{{cite web|url=http://www.veloarchive.com/races/tour/1950.php|author=Tom James|date=14 August 2003|accessdate=3 December 2009|publisher=Veloarchive|title=1950: K\u00fcbler wins after the Italians withdraw}}</ref> although the yellow jersey for the leader of the general classification was exchanged between Luxembourgian Jean Goldschmit and French Bernard Gauthier.\n\n[[File:Ferdi K\u00fcbler 1954.jpg|thumb|left|upright|[[Ferdinand K\u00fcbler]] ''(pictured in 1954)'' won three stages on his way to winning the [[General classification in the Tour de France|general classification]]]]\nThe sixth stage was won by Swiss cyclist [[Ferdinand K\u00fcbler]]. During the race, K\u00fcbler had changed jerseys, which gave him 25 seconds penalty time.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.archiefleeuwardercourant.nl/site/article.do?code=LC&date=19500720&id=LC-19500720-7004|publisher=Leeuwarder Courant|date=20 July 1950|language=Dutch|accessdate=3 December 2009|title=K\u00fcbler won de tijdrit en Goldschmidt kreeg de gele trui}}</ref>\n\nIn the eleventh stage, the first mountain stage of the race, [[Gino Bartali]] was away together with French [[Jean Robic]]. There was a lot of crowd, and they pressed forward to see the cyclist coming.<ref name=\"revealed\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cyclingrevealed.com/timeline/Race%20Snippets/TdF/TdF1950.htm|title=The \"Suisse Cowboy\" Inherits the Win|author=Barry Boyce|year=2004|accessdate=3 December 2009|publisher=Cycling revealed}}</ref> This caused Bartali to fall down during the descent of the [[Col d'Aspin]], and this caused Robic to also fall down.<ref name=\"veloarchive\"/> Bartali got up and won the stage, but felt threatened by spectators, who punched and kicked him. One spectator had threatened Bartali with a knife.<ref name=\"revealed\"/> Bartali told his team manager [[Alfredo Binda]] that he was leaving the Tour de France, and that all Italian cyclists should abandon the race.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=165\u2013173}} Not all Italian cyclists wanted to leave: the members from the second Italian team (the Italian Cadets) and Adolfo Leoni wanted to stay. Some Italian cyclists said they wanted to stay in the race to help Magni defend the leading position.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=165\u2013173}} Magni felt bad about giving up the chance to win the Tour de France, but accepted the decision.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bikeraceinfo.com/oralhistory/magni.html|title=Fiorenzo Magni, a bridge between the legendary past and the modern era of cycling|publisher=Bike Race Info|author=Valeria Paoletti and Bill McGann|accessdate=3 December 2009}}</ref> The Tour organisation wanted to keep the Italian cyclists in the race, and among other compromises offered to give them neutral gray jerseys, so the spectators would not recognize them.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=165\u2013173}} None of this helped, and both Italian teams left the race. As a consequence, the fifteenth stage, that was originally scheduled to end in Italy ([[Sanremo]]), was rescheduled to end in Menton.<ref name=\"letour.fr\">{{cite web|url=http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/us/TDF/1950/histoire.html|title=The Tour - Year 1950|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|accessdate=3 December 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090716155401/http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/us/TDF/1950/histoire.html|archive-date=16 July 2009|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable floatright\"\n|+ General classification after stage 11 (1\u20136)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1947_1977/tdf1950_11.php|publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme|title=37\u00e8me Tour de France 1950 - 11\u00e8me \u00e9tape|language=French|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120302191753/http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1947_1977/tdf1950_11.php|archive-date=2 March 2012|access-date=26 September 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Rank!! scope=\"col\" | Rider!! scope=\"col\" | Team!! scope=\"col\" | Time\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |1\n| {{flagathlete|[[Fiorenzo Magni]]|ITA}} [[File:Jersey yellow.svg|20px|alt=Yellow Jersey]] || Italy || style=\"text-align:right;\" |   73h 23' 11\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |2\n| {{flagathlete|[[Ferdinand K\u00fcbler]]|SUI}} || Switzerland || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 2' 31\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |3\n| {{flagathlete|[[Louison Bobet]]|FRA}} || France || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 3' 20\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |4\n| {{flagathlete|[[Rapha\u00ebl G\u00e9miniani]]|FRA}} || France || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 3' 25\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |5\n| {{flagathlete|[[Stan Ockers]]|BEL}} || Belgium || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 3' 37\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |6\n| {{flagathlete|[[Gino Bartali]]|ITA}} || Italy || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 4' 17\"\n|}\nWith Magni out of the race, Swiss [[Ferdinand K\u00fcbler]] became the new leader of the general classification, closely followed by Bobet and Geminiani. Out of respect for Magni, K\u00fcbler did not wear the yellow jersey (indicating the leader in the general classification) in the 12th stage.\nIn the twelfth stage, all the favourites finished together. That stage was won by Belgian [[Maurice Blomme]], but not without difficulties: he was so exhausted that he mistook a dark shadow for the finish line, and stopped racing. The secretary of the Tour de France, [[Jean Garnault]], had to put him back on his bicycle so he would ride the last meters of the stage.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.archiefleeuwardercourant.nl/site/article.do?code=LC&date=19500727&id=LC-19500727-5003|title=Belg Blomme won 12e etappe|language=Dutch|publisher=Leeuwarder Courant|date=27 July 1950|accessdate=3 December 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn that stage thirteen, the temperature was extremely high. Two riders from the North African team, [[Marcel Molin\u00e8s]] and [[Abdel-Kader Zaaf]], broke away after 15 kilometers, and created a large gap, also because the other cyclists were more occupied with getting drinks.<ref name=\"cwszaaf\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cyclingwebsite.net/coureurfiche.php?coureurid=6621|title=Abdel-Kader Zaaf|author=Tom Vandenbussche|language=Dutch|publisher=Cyclingwebsite|accessdate=3 December 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081011141905/http://www.cyclingwebsite.net/coureurfiche.php?coureurid=6621|archive-date=11 October 2008|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref> Some 20 kilometers from the finish, Zaaf started to zigzag across the road. A safety official pulled him from the race, afraid for his safety, and Molin\u00e8s rode through alone. Zaaf did not agree with the safety official, and mounted his bicycle again. He quickly fell off his bicycle and fell asleep, and spectators moved him into the shade of a tree.<ref name=\"cwszaaf\"/> When he woke up, he realised that he was in a race, got on his bicycle again and rode away, but going into the wrong direction. An ambulance was called, and Zaaf was taken away. Zaaf claimed that he had received wine from a spectator, and as a Muslim he was not used to the alcohol.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=165\u2013173}} Behind the two North-African cyclists, K\u00fcbler had attacked, and left his rivals [[Rapha\u00ebl G\u00e9miniani]] and [[Louison Bobet]] minutes behind.<ref name=\"veloarchive\"/> Of the favourites, only Ockers managed to stay with K\u00fcbler.\n\nIn stage fifteen, it was still hot, and the riders were not motivated to race. They stopped during the race to cool down in the [[Mediterranean Sea]], but were quickly ordered by [[Jacques Goddet]] to continue the race.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=165\u2013173}} The journalists that followed the race reported on this in a humorous way, and the organisation therefore fined them.<ref>Thompson, p.217</ref>\n\nIn the sixteenth stage, Ockers and Bobet finished shortly after K\u00fcbler. The Tour de France jury said Bobet came in second, and gave him the 30 seconds bonification time, but the Belgian team manager [[Sylv\u00e8re Maes]] protested against this decision, because he argued that Ockers came in second. Maes threatened to take the Belgian team out of the race, but the Tour direction did not change their decision. In the end, the Belgian team stayed in the race.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.archiefleeuwardercourant.nl/site/article.do?code=LC&date=19500801&id=LC-19500801-2008|title=Dreigement van Sylver Maes|publisher=Leeuwarder Courant|date=1 August 1950|accessdate=3 December 2009|language=Dutch}}</ref>\n\nSecond placed rider in the general classification, Ockers was unable to win back time in later stages, so K\u00fcbler stayed in the lead for the rest of the race, and became the first Swiss winner of the Tour de France.\n\nK\u00fcbler's victory is seen as partially his own accomplishment, but also partially due to the absence of Fausto Coppi and the withdrawal of the Italian teams.{{sfn|Whittle|2003|p=113}} According to K\u00fcbler, it became more difficult to win the race after the Italians had left the race, because the attention was no longer focussed on the Italians, but on K\u00fcbler. K\u00fcbler felt that he would have been able to win the 1950 Tour de France if the Italians would have not abandoned, because he was the best in the time trials.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bikeraceinfo.com/oralhistory/kubler.html|title=Ferdy K\u00fcbler, 1950 Tour Winner, Answers Some Questions|publisher=Bike Race Info|date=23 September 2004|accessdate=3 December 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Classification leadership and minor prizes==\n\n[[File:Wiemu17.jpg|thumb|The [[Team classification in the Tour de France|team classification]] trophy for 1950, won by the Belgium team]]\nThe time that each cyclist required to finish each stage was recorded, and these times were added together for the [[general classification in the Tour de France|general classification]]. If a cyclist had received a time bonus, it was subtracted from this total; all time penalties were added to this total. The cyclist with the least accumulated time was the race leader, identified by the yellow jersey.{{sfn|Nauright|Parrish|2012|pp=452\u2013453}} The total prize money in the 1950 Tour de France was 14 million French Francs; 1 million French Francs were for the winner of the general classification.{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=41}} Of the 116 cyclists that started the 1959 Tour de France, 51 finished the race.\n\nPoints for the [[mountains classification in the Tour de France|mountains classification]] were earned by reaching the mountain tops first.{{sfn|Nauright|Parrish|2012|p=454}} The system was the same as in 1949: there were two types of mountain tops: the hardest ones, in category 1, gave 10 points to the first cyclist, the easier ones, in category 2, gave 5 points to the first cyclist, and the easiest ones, in category 3, gave 3 points. Louison Bobet won this classification after having led the classification almost the entire race, although he only reached 2 of the 14 mountain tops first.<ref name=\"mdc1950\"/>\n\nThe [[Team classification in the Tour de France|team classification]] was calculated by adding the times in the general classification of the best three cyclists per team.{{sfn|Nauright|Parrish|2012|p=455}} It was won by the Belgian team, with a large margin over the French team. Of the other four teams that started, the two Italian teams had abandoned the race, and the North African team finished with only two riders and the Dutch team with only one rider, therefore they were ineligible for the team classification. The [[Souvenir Henri Desgrange]] was given in honour of Tour founder [[Henri Desgrange]] to the first rider to pass the summit of the [[Col du Lautaret]] on stage 19. This prize was won by [[Apo Lazarid\u00e8s]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Bobet diep ontgoocheld na grootse vlucht|trans-title=Bobet deeply disappointed after a great flight|url=https://resolver.kb.nl/resolve?urn=ddd:110585112:mpeg21:p005|work=[[De Telegraaf]]|date=4 August 1950|page=5|language=Dutch|via=[[Delpher]]}}</ref> The special award for the best regional rider was won by sixth-placed [[Kl\u00e9ber Piot]].{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=41}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:smaller; clear:both;\"\n|+Classification leadership by stage<ref name=\"tdf-statistics\">{{cite web|last=van den Akker|first=Pieter|title=Informatie over de Tour de France van 1950|trans-title=Information about the Tour de France from 1950|url=http://www.tourdefrancestatistieken.nl/tour.php?jaar=1950|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190302050053/http://www.tourdefrancestatistieken.nl/tour.php?jaar=1950|archive-date=2 March 2019|language=Dutch|website=TourDeFranceStatistieken.nl|accessdate=2 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:1%;\"| Stage\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:24%;\"| Winner\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:24%;\"| [[General classification in the Tour de France|General classification]]<br />[[File:Jersey yellow.svg|25px|alt=|link=]]\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:24%;\"| [[Mountains classification in the Tour de France|Mountains classification]]{{efn|name=mountains-jersey|No jersey was awarded to the leader of the mountains classification until a white jersey with red [[polka dot]]s was introduced in [[1975 Tour de France|1975]].{{sfn|Nauright|Parrish|2012|p=454}}}}\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:24%;\"| [[Team classification in the Tour de France|Team classification]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 1\n| [[Jean Goldschmit]]\n| style=\"background:#FFEB64;\" rowspan=\"2\"| [[Jean Goldschmit]]\n| rowspan=\"10\"| ''no award''\n| rowspan=\"2\"| Luxembourg\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2\n| [[Adolfo Leoni]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 3\n| [[Alfredo Pasotti]]\n| style=\"background:#FFEB64;\" rowspan=\"3\"| [[Bernard Gauthier]]\n| rowspan=\"3\"| South-East\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 4\n| [[Stan Ockers]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 5\n| [[Giovanni Corrieri]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 6\n| [[Ferdinand K\u00fcbler]]\n| style=\"background:#FFEB64;\"| [[Jean Goldschmit]]\n| Belgium\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 7\n| [[Nello Lauredi]]\n| style=\"background:#FFEB64;\" rowspan=\"4\"| [[Bernard Gauthier]]\n| rowspan=\"4\"| South-East\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 8\n| [[Fiorenzo Magni]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 9\n| [[Alfredo Pasotti]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 10\n| [[Marcel Dussault]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 11\n| [[Gino Bartali]]\n| style=\"background:#FFEB64;\"| [[Fiorenzo Magni]]\n| rowspan=\"6\"| [[Louison Bobet]]\n| Italy\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 12\n| [[Maurice Blomme]]\n| style=\"background:#FFEB64;\" rowspan=\"11\"| [[Ferdinand K\u00fcbler]]\n| France\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 13\n| [[Marcel Molin\u00e8s]]\n| rowspan=\"10\"| Belgium\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 14\n| [[Custodio Dos Reis]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 15\n| [[Jean Diederich]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 16\n| [[Ferdinand K\u00fcbler]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 17\n| [[Rapha\u00ebl G\u00e9miniani]]\n| [[Jean Robic]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 18\n| [[Louison Bobet]]\n| rowspan=\"5\"| [[Louison Bobet]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 19\n| [[Rapha\u00ebl G\u00e9miniani]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 20\n| [[Ferdinand K\u00fcbler]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 21\n| [[Gino Sciardis]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 22\n| [[\u00c9mile Baffert]]\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | Final\n! style=\"background:#FFDB00;\"|[[Ferdinand K\u00fcbler]]\n! [[Louison Bobet]]\n! Belgium\n|}\n\n==Final standings==\n\n===General classification===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:38em; margin-bottom:0;\"\n|+ Final general classification (1\u201310)<ref name=\"mdc1950\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Rank!! scope=\"col\" | Rider!! scope=\"col\" | Team!! scope=\"col\" | Time\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |1\n| {{flagathlete|[[Ferdinand K\u00fcbler]]|SUI}} || Switzerland || style=\"text-align:right;\" |   145h 36' 56\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |2\n| {{flagathlete|[[Stan Ockers]]|BEL}} || Belgium || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 9' 30\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |3\n| {{flagathlete|[[Louison Bobet]]|FRA}} || France || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 22' 19\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |4\n| {{flagathlete|[[Rapha\u00ebl G\u00e9miniani]]|FRA}} || France || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 31' 14\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |5\n| {{flagathlete|[[Jean Kirchen]]|LUX}} || Luxembourg || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 34' 21\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |6\n| {{flagathlete|[[Kl\u00e9ber Piot]]|FRA}} || \u00cele-de-France/North-East || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 41' 35\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |7\n| {{flagathlete|[[Pierre Cogan]]|FRA}} || Centre/South-West || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 52' 22\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |8\n| {{flagathlete|[[Raymond Impanis]]|BEL}} || Belgium || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 53' 34\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |9\n| {{flagathlete|[[Georges Meunier]]|FRA}} || Centre/South-West || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 54' 29\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |10\n| {{flagathlete|[[Jean Goldschmit]]|LUX}} || Luxembourg || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 55' 21\"\n|}\n{| class=\"collapsible collapsed wikitable\" style=\"width:38em;margin-top:-1px;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"4\" | Final general classification (11\u201351)\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Rank!! scope=\"col\" | Rider!! scope=\"col\" | Team!! scope=\"col\" | Time\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |11\n| {{flagathlete|[[Pierre Brambilla]]|FRA}} || South-East || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 57' 14\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |12\n| {{flagathlete|[[Jean Robic]]|FRA}} || West || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 59' 45\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |13\n| {{flagathlete|[[Roger Lambrecht]]|BEL}} || Belgium || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 1h 00' 29\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |14\n| {{flagathlete|[[Andr\u00e9 Brul\u00e9 (cyclist)|Andr\u00e9 Brul\u00e9]]|FRA}} ||\u00cele-de-France/North-East  || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 1h 05' 29\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |15\n| {{flagathlete|[[Marcel Verschueren]]|BEL}} || Belgium Aiglons || s