n\n===Mountains classification===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Final mountains classification (1\u20139)<ref>{{cite news|title=Coppi \u00e8 il drappo svettante di una baniera impugnata da Bartali|trans-title=Coppi and the towering drape of a basket held by Bartali|url=http://dlib.coninet.it/bookreader.php?&c=1&f=7610|work=[[Corriere dello Sport]]|date=25 July 1949|page=2|language=Italian|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191004134838/http://dlib.coninet.it/bookreader.php?&c=1&f=7610|archive-date=10 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Rank!! scope=\"col\" | Rider!! scope=\"col\" | Team!! scope=\"col\" | Points\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |1\n| {{flagathlete|[[Fausto Coppi]]|ITA}} || Italy || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 81\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |2\n| {{flagathlete|[[Gino Bartali]]|ITA}} || Italy || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 68\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |3\n| {{flagathlete|[[Jean Robic]]|FRA}} || West/North || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 64\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |4\n| {{flagathlete|[[Apo Lazarid\u00e8s]]|FRA}} || France || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 48\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |5\n| {{flagathlete|[[Lucien Lazarid\u00e8s]]|FRA}} || France || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 29\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |6\n| {{flagathlete|[[Stan Ockers]]|BEL}} || Belgium || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 22\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"2\" |7\n| {{flagathlete|[[Giuseppe Tacca]]|FRA}} || \u00cele-de-France || style=\"text-align:right;\" rowspan=\"2\" | 16\n|-\n| {{flagathlete|[[Jacques Marinelli]]|FRA}} || \u00cele-de-France\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"2\" |9\n| {{flagathlete|[[Rapha\u00ebl G\u00e9miniani]]|FRA}} || France || style=\"text-align:right;\" rowspan=\"2\" | 14\n|-\n| {{flagathlete|[[Andr\u00e9 Brul\u00e9 (cyclist)|Andr\u00e9 Brul\u00e9]]|FRA}} || \u00cele-de-France\n|}\n\n{{column}}\n\n===Team classification===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Final team classification<ref name=\"veloarchive\">{{cite web|url=http://www.veloarchive.com/races/tour/1949.php|first=Tom|last=James|date=14 August 2003|accessdate=2 December 2009|publisher=Veloarchive|title=1949: Coppi's double}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca-paginas.mundodeportivo.com/EMD02/HEM/1949/07/25/MD19490725-003.pdf|date=25 July 1947|language=Spanish|title=Termin\u00f3 la Vuelta a Francia|work=[[Mundo Deportivo]]|page=3|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160312165615/http://hemeroteca-paginas.mundodeportivo.com/EMD02/HEM/1949/07/25/MD19490725-003.pdf|archive-date=12 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Rank!! scope=\"col\" | Team!! scope=\"col\" | Time\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |1\n| Italy || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 450h 35' 23\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |2\n| West/North || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 2h 10' 21\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |3\n| Luxembourg || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 2h 18' 16\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |4\n| France || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 2h 33' 08\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |5\n| \u00cele-de-France || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 2h 41' 36\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |6\n| Belgium || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 3h 00' 13\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |7\n| Belgium Aiglons || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 3h 21' 25\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |8\n| South-East || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 5h 49' 25\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |9\n| Centre/South-West || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 8h 15' 30\"\n|}\n\n{{columns-end}}\n\n==Aftermath==\nAs Coppi had also won the [[1949 Giro d'Italia]], he became the first person to achieve the Giro-Tour double.<ref name=\"veloarchive\"/>\n\nAfter the unrest in Aosta and Colmar, there were doubts if the Italian cyclists would return in 1950, and if that Tour should pass through Italy again.<ref>{{cite newspaper|url=http://resolver.kb.nl/resolve?urn=ddd:011239483:mpeg21:a0103|title=Geminiani en Goasmat brachten vuur in etappe naar Colmar|trans-title=Geminiani and Goasmat put fire into the stage to Colmar|date=23 July 1949|accessdate=5 March 2018|via=Delpher|newspaper=[[De Gooi- en Eemlander]]|page=5|language=Dutch}}</ref> At the start of the [[1950 Tour de France]], the Italian team was present and the Tour was scheduled to go through Italy, but after further incidents the Italian team left the race, and the stage through Italy was rerouted.\n\nCoppi would go on to repeat the Giro-Tour double in 1952.\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book|first=Jacques|last=Augendre|author-link=Jacques Augendre|url=http://netstorage.lequipe.fr/ASO/cyclisme/le-tour/2016/histoire/TDF16_GH_Interactif-PROD.pdf|title=Guide historique|trans-title=Historical guide|year=2016|language=French|access-date=27 October 2016|format=PDF|work=[[Tour de France]]|location=Paris|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817121602/http://netstorage.lequipe.fr/ASO/cyclisme/le-tour/2016/histoire/TDF16_GH_Interactif-PROD.pdf|archive-date=17 August 2016|url-status=live|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=McGann|first1=Bill|last2=McGann|first2=Carol|title=The Story of the Tour de France: 1903\u20131964|volume=1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jxq20JskqMUC|publisher=Dog Ear Publishing|location=Indianapolis, IN|year=2006|isbn=978-1-59858-180-5|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Seray|first1=Jacques|last2=Lablaine|first2=Jacques|author-link1=:fr:Jacques Seray|title=Henri Desgrange, l'homme qui cr\u00e9a le Tour de France|trans-title=Henri Desgrange, the man who created the Tour de France|language=French|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EKgTAQAAIAAJ|publisher=Editions Cristel|location=Saint-Malo, France|year=2006|isbn=978-2-84421-042-5|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Nauright|first1=John|last2=Parrish|first2=Charles|title=Sports Around the World: History, Culture, and Practice|volume=2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IkLYDgTnMxEC|year=2012|publisher=[[ABC-CLIO]]|location=Santa Barbara, CA|isbn=978-1-59884-300-2|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category-inline|Tour de Fra