xt-align:center;\" | {{convert|261|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s) ||{{flagathlete|[[Gino Bartali]]|ITA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 9 July\n| colspan=\"2\" | [[Toulouse]]\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" | Rest day\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |9\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 10 July\n| [[Toulouse]] to [[Montpellier]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|246|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage ||{{flagathlete|[[Raymond Impanis]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |10\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 11 July\n| [[Montpellier]] to [[Marseille]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|248|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage ||{{flagathlete|[[Raymond Impanis]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |11\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 12 July\n| [[Marseille]] to [[Sanremo]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|245|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage ||{{flagathlete|[[Gino Sciardis]]|ITA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |12\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 13 July\n| [[Sanremo]] to [[Cannes]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|170|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s) ||{{flagathlete|[[Louison Bobet]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 14 July\n| colspan=\"2\" | [[Cannes]]\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" | Rest day\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |13\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 15 July\n| [[Cannes]] to [[Brian\u00e7on]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|274|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s) ||{{flagathlete|[[Gino Bartali]]|ITA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |14\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 16 July\n| [[Brian\u00e7on]] to [[Aix-les-Bains]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|263|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s) ||{{flagathlete|[[Gino Bartali]]|ITA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 17 July\n| colspan=\"2\" | [[Aix-les-Bains]]\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" | Rest day\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |15\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 18 July\n| [[Aix-les-Bains]] to [[Lausanne]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|256|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s) ||{{flagathlete|[[Gino Bartali]]|ITA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |16\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 19 July\n| [[Lausanne]] to [[Mulhouse]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|243|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s) ||{{flagathlete|[[Edward Van Dijck]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 20 July\n| colspan=\"2\" | [[Mulhouse]]\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" | Rest day\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |17\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 21 July\n| [[Mulhouse]] to [[Strasbourg]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|120|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Time Trial.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || [[Individual time trial]] ||{{flagathlete|[[Roger Lambrecht]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |18\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 22 July\n| [[Strasbourg]] to [[Metz]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|195|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage ||{{flagathlete|[[Giovanni Corrieri]]|ITA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |19\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 23 July\n| [[Metz]] to [[Li\u00e8ge]] (Belgium)|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|249|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage ||{{flagathlete|[[Gino Bartali]]|ITA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |20\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 24 July\n| [[Li\u00e8ge]] (Belgium) to [[Roubaix]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|228|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage ||{{flagathlete|[[Bernard Gauthier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |21\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 25 July\n| [[Roubaix]] to [[Paris]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|286|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage ||{{flagathlete|[[Giovanni Corrieri]]|ITA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"| Total\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center\"| {{convert|4922|km|0|abbr=on}}{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=109}}\n|}\n\n==Race overview==\n[[File:Tourde France 1948 margin.svg|thumb|alt=Graph with \"Margin\" on the y-axis and \"Stage\" on the x-axis. The x-axis goes from 1 to 21, and the graph starts at stage 1 at 0:00, rises to above 20:00 but returns to 0:00 at stage 13.|The margin between Gino Bartali and the leader of the race in the 1948 Tour de France. After the twelfth stage, the margin reached it maximum at 21:28, but after that it quickly went down.]]\nAs the Italian team had not entered the Tours de France of 1939 and 1947, it was the first Tour de France for Bartali since his victory ten years before in 1938. His results in the [[Giro d'Italia]] had not been well, and it was not thought that Bartali could compete for the win.<ref name=\"veloarchive\">{{cite web|url=http://www.veloarchive.com/races/tour/1948.php|publisher=Veloarchive|author=Tom James|date=15 August 2003|accessdate=2 December 2009|title=1948: Bartali saves Italy}}</ref>\n\nBartali however won the sprint in the first stage, and thanks to the bonification of one minute for the winner, he was leading the race. After that, the Italian team took a low profile in the race.<ref name=\"veloarchive\"/>\nIn the second stage, Bartali lost the lead already; although his teammate [[Vincenzo Rossello]] won the stage, Belgian [[Jan Engels]] took over the yellow jersey.{{sfn|Amels|1984|p=56}}\n\nIn the third stage, a group escaped and built up a lead of almost 14 minutes. Among that group was [[Louison Bobet]], and as he was the best-placed cyclist in that group he became the next leader. Also in that group was [[Roger Lambrecht]]; when Lambrecht again was able to be in the first group in the fourth stage, he took the lead, becoming the fourth rider in four stages to don the yellow jersey. Lambrecht kept it in the next stage, but after Bobet won the sixth stage, Bobet took back the lead, and the yellow jersey made him confident.{{sfn|Amels|1984|p=56}} In the Pyren\u00e9es, Bartali won both stages in a sprint, but Bobet was near and became the hero of the French spectators.{{sfn|Amels|1984|p=56}}\n\nAfter the ninth stage, Bobet had built up a lead of more than nine minutes. In the tenth stage, he lost time, and Belgian cyclist [[Roger Lambrecht]] reduced the margin to 29 seconds. After the eleventh stage, Bobet was still in the lead, but was having problems, and after he fainted at the finish, he wanted to give up. After a meal, massage and sleeping, he changed his mind, and won the twelfth stage.<ref name=\"letour.fr\">{{cite web|url=http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/us/TDF/1948/histoire.html|title=The Tour - Year 1948|publisher=letour.fr|author=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|accessdate=2 December 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100225041159/http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/us/TDF/1948/histoire.html|archive-date=25 February 2010|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAfter the twelfth stage, Bartali was 20 minutes behind. Bartali thought about quitting the tour, but was persuaded to race on.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://outside.away.com/outside/events/column/col0705.html|title=Looking back: Tour de France 1948|author=Bill Henderson|date=5 July 1996|accessdate=2 December 2009|publisher=away.com}}</ref> That night, Bartali received a phone call while he was in bed. [[Alcide De Gasperi]], prime minister of Italy, from the [[Christian Democracy (Italy)|Christian Democratic party]], told him that a few days earlier [[Palmiro Togliatti]], leader of the [[Italian Communist Party]], had been shot, and Italy might be on the edge of a civil war. De Gasperi asked Bartali to do his best to win a stage, because the sport news might distract people from the politics. Bartali replied that he would do better, and win the race.<ref name=\"veloarchive\"/>\nThe next day, Bartali won stage 13 with a large margin. In the general classification, he jumped to second place, trailing by only 66 seconds. In the fourteenth stage, Bartali and Bobet rode together over the Galibier and the Croix de Fer, but Bartali had been saving his energy, and left Bobet and every body else behind on the Col de Porte. Bartali won again, and took over the yellow jersey as leader of the general classification. Bobet was now in second place, eight minutes behind. The next stage, stage 15, was also won by Bartali.\nThe sixteenth stage was not won by Bartali, but because his direct competitors lost time, he increased his lead to 32 minutes.<ref name=\"veloarchive\"/> Bartali lost minutes in the time trial in stage 17, but his lead was never endangered.\n\nWith each stage win of Bartali (seven in total), the Italian excitement about the Tour de France increased, and the political tensions quieted.<ref name=\"revealed\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cyclingrevealed.com/timeline/Race%20Snippets/TdF/TdF1948.htm|title=Gino \"the Pious,\" an Inspirational Win|author=Barry Boyce|year=2004|accessdate=2 December 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Classification leadership and minor prizes==\n\nThe time that each cyclist required to finish each stage was recorded, and these times were added together for the [[general classification in the Tour de France|general classification]]. If a cyclist had received a time bonus, it was subtracted from this total; all time penalties were added to this total. The cyclist with the least accumulated time was the race leader, identified by the yellow jersey.{{sfn|Nauright|Parrish|2012|pp=452\u2013453}} The budget of the Tour de France in 1948 was 45 million Francs, from which one third was provided by private enterprises.<ref>Dauncey, p.110</ref> In total, 7 million Francs of prizes were awarded in the 1948 Tour de France. Of these, 600.000 Francs were given to Bartali for winning the general classification.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/us/TDF/1948/index.html|title=l'Historique du Tour de France, Ann\u00e9e 1948|publisher=letour.fr|author=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|accessdate=2 December 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090715154737/http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/us/TDF/1948/index.html|archive-date=15 July 2009|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Bartali is the only cyclist to win two Tours de France ten years apart.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=156\u2013159}} Of the 120 cyclists, 44 finished the race.\n\nPoints for the [[Mountains classification in the Tour de France|mountains classification]] were earned by reaching the mountain tops first.{{sfn|Nauright|Parrish|2012|p=454}} There were two types of mountain tops: the hardest ones, in category A, gave 10 points to the first cyclist, the easier ones, in category B, gave 5 points to the first cyclist.\n\nThe [[Team classification in the Tour de France|team classification]] was calculated by adding the times in the general classification of the best three cyclists per team.{{sfn|Nauright|Parrish|2012|p=455}}\n\nThe [[Souvenir Henri Desgrange]] was given in honour of Tour founder [[Henri Desgrange]] in the opening few kilometres of stage 1 at the summit of the [[:fr:Avenue des \u00c9tats-Unis (Versailles)|C\u00f4te de Picardie]] in [[Versailles, Yvelines|Versailles]], Paris.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.memoire-du-cyclisme.eu/eta_tdf_1947_1949/tdf1948_1.php|work=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme|title=35\u00e8me Tour de France 1948 - 1\u00e8re \u00e9tape|trans-title=35th Tour de France 1948 - 1st stage|language=French|access-date=19 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191202164631/http://www.memoire-du-cyclisme.eu/eta_tdf_1947_1949/tdf1948_1.php|archive-date=2 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"1948-parool\">{{cite news|title=Tour de France begonnen|trans-title=Tour de France begins|url=https://resolver.kb.nl/resolve?urn=ABCDDD:010830971:mpeg21:p003|work=[[Het Parool]]|date=30 June 1948|page=3|language=Dutch|via=[[Delpher]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Versailles: les statues de La Fayette et Pershing inaugur\u00e9es |trans-title=Versailles: La Fayette and Pershing statues inaugurated |url=http://www.leparisien.fr/yvelines-78/versailles-78000/versailles-les-statues-de-la-fayette-et-pershing-inaugurees-05-10-2017-7309599.php |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=[[Le Parisien]] |date=5 October 2017 |language=French|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191202164707/http://www.leparisien.fr/yvelines-78/versailles-78000/versailles-les-statues-de-la-fayette-et-pershing-inaugurees-05-10-2017-7309599.php|archive-date=2 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> This prize was won by [[Roger Lambrecht]].<ref name=\"1948-parool\" /> The Tour de France in 1948 for the first time had a special award for the best regional rider.<ref name=\"letour.fr\"/> This was won by third-placed [[Guy Lap\u00e9bie]].{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=39}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:smaller; clear:both;\"\n|+Classification leadership by stage<ref name=\"tdf-statistics\">{{cite web|last=van den Akker|first=Pieter|title=Informatie over de Tour de France van 1948|trans-title=Information about the Tour de France from 1948|url=http://www.tourdefrancestatistieken.nl/tour.php?jaar=1948|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190302050036/http://www.tourdefrancestatistieken.nl/tour.php?jaar=1948|archivedate=2 March 2019|language=Dutch|website=TourDeFranceStatistieken.nl|accessdate=2 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:1%;\"| Stage\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:24%;\"| Winner\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:24%;\"| [[General classification in the Tour de France|General classification]]<br />[[File:Jersey yellow.svg|25px|alt=|link=]]\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:24%;\"| [[Mountains classification in the Tour de France|Mountains classification]]{{efn|name=mountains-jersey|No jersey was awarded to the leader of the mountains classification until a white jersey with red [[polka dot]]s was introduced in 1975.<ref name=\"jerseys\">{{cite news|last=Cunningham|first=Josh|title=History of the Tour de France jerseys|url=http://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/1409/history-of-the-tour-de-france-jerseys|accessdate=2 October 2016|work=Cyclist|publisher=[[Dennis Publishing]]|date=4 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161026180408/http://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/1409/history-of-the-tour-de-france-jerseys|archive-date=26 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>}}\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:24%;\"| [[Team classification in the Tour de France|Team classification]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 1\n| [[Gino Bartali]]\n| style=\"background:#FFEB64;\"| [[Gino Bartali]]\n| rowspan=\"6\"| ''no award''\n| Belgium\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2\n| [[Vincenzo Rossello]]\n| style=\"background:#FFEB64;\"| [[Jan Engels]]\n| Belgium B\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 3\n| [[Guy Lap\u00e9bie]]\n| style=\"background:#FFEB64;\"| [[Louison Bobet]]\n| France\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 4\n| [[Jacques Pras]]\n| style=\"background:#FFEB64;\" rowspan=\"2\"| [[Roger Lambrecht]]\n| rowspan=\"3\"| Internationals\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 5\n| [[Raoul Remy]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 6\n| [[Louison Bobet]]\n| style=\"background:#FFEB64;\" rowspan=\"8\"| [[Louison Bobet]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 7\n| [[Gino Bartali]]\n| [[Bernard Gauthier]]\n| rowspan=\"3\"| France\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 8\n| [[Gino Bartali]]\n| rowspan=\"6\"| [[Jean Robic]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 9\n| [[Raymond Impanis]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 10\n| [[Raymond Impanis]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"| Internationals\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 11\n| [[Gino Sciardis]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 12\n| [[Louison Bobet]]\n| rowspan=\"5\"| France\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 13\n| [[Gino Bartali]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 14\n| [[Gino Bartali]]\n| style=\"background:#FFEB64;\" rowspan=\"8\"| [[Gino Bartali]]\n| rowspan=\"8\"| [[Gino