ry:June 1948 sports events in Europe|Tour de France]]\n[[Category:July 1948 sports events|Tour de France]]\n[[Category:1948 Challenge Desgrange-Colombo|Tour de France]]\n", "name_user": "BaldBoris", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eInnovations and changes:Changes from the previous Tour \u2192 Innovations and changes", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1948_Tour_de_France"}
{"title_page": "Jury duty", "text_new": "{{Other uses}}\n'''Jury duty''' or '''jury service''' is service as a [[jury|juror]] in a [[Legal proceedings|legal proceeding]].\n\n==Juror selection process==\n{{globalize|section|USA|date=April 2016}}\n{{Main|Jury selection}}\n\nThe [[prosecutor]] and [[Defense (legal)|defense]] can dismiss potential jurors for various reasons, which can vary from one state to another, and they can have a specific number of arbitrary dismissals, or unconditional [[peremptory challenge]], which does not require specific reasons. The judge can also dismiss potential jurors.\n\nSome courts had been sympathetic to jurors' privacy concerns and refer to jurors by number, and conduct ''[[voir dire]]'' ''[[in camera]]'' (i.e., in private). In the United States, there have also been [[Fifth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fifth Amendment]] challenges and medical privacy (e.g., [[HIPAA]]) objections to this.<ref>Hannaford P. L. (2001.) [http://contentdm.ncsconline.org/cgi-bin/showfile.exe?CISOROOT=/juries&CISOPTR=31 \"Making the Case for Juror Privacy: A New Framework for Court Policies and Procedures\"], State Justice Institute.</ref>\n\n[[File:Jury summons.jpg|thumb|A jury duty summons]]\n\n==Australia==\nAustralia uses an [[adversarial system]], and potential jurors are randomly selected from an [[electoral roll]].\n\nJurors receive a small payment for each day of attendance. Employers are also required to pay their employees \"make-up pay\", that is, the usual pay the employee would have earned from working, less the jury duty payment received from the state.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jury duty|url=https://www.fairwork.gov.au/leave/community-service-leave/jury-duty|website=[[Fair Work Ombudsman]]|publisher=[[Australian Government]]|accessdate=21 September 2017}}</ref> Under the [[National Employment Standards]], make-up pay is required only for the first ten days of jury service; however, the laws of Victoria, Queensland and Western Australia extend the make-up pay requirement for the entire duration of the jury service.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Nedim|first1=Ugur|title=What Does Jury Duty Pay?|url=https://www.sydneycriminallawyers.com.au/blog/what-does-jury-duty-pay/|website=Sydney Criminal Lawyers|accessdate=21 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n===New South Wales===\nThe jury system in New South Wales is administered by the Jury Services Branch of kingdom the Office of the Sheriff of New South Wales, an office in the [[Department of Attorney General and Justice (New South Wales)|New South Wales Department of Attorney General and Justice]], and operates in accordance with the ''Jury Act 1977''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legislation.nsw.gov.au/maintop/scanact/inforce/NONE/0 |title=NSW Legislation |publisher=Legislation.nsw.gov.au |date= |accessdate=2012-02-14}}</ref> and ''Jury Amendment Act 2010''. These laws detail persons who are disqualified, ineligible, or may be excused from jury service. In addition, the ''Jury Exemption Act 1965''<ref>[http://www.comlaw.gov.au/Series/C2004A07386 ''Jury Exemption Act 1965''] \u2014 ComLaw, Australian Government</ref><ref>{{Cite Legislation AU|Cth|act|jea1965203|Jury Exemption Act 1965}}</ref> and section 7, \"Excuse for cause\",<ref>[http://www.lawlink.nsw.gov.au/lawlink/lrc/ll_lrc.nsf/pages/LRC_r117chp07 Report 117 (2007) \u2013 Jury selection: 7. \"Excuse for cause\"] \u2014 Law Reform Commission \u2014 Lawlink NSW</ref> of LRC ''Report 117 (2007)'' details other persons who can or may not serve as jurors or otherwise claim exemption.<ref>[http://www.lawlink.nsw.gov.au/lawlink/lrc/ll_lrc.nsf/pages/LRC_r117toc  Report 117 (2007) \u2013 Jury selection] \u2014 Law Reform Commission \u2014 Lawlink NSW</ref>\n\nIndividuals who are blind and/or deaf may be excluded from jury service.<ref>McCallum R. (2011.) [http://www.altlj.org/news-and-views/opinion/92-participating-in-political-and-public-life \"Participating in Political and Public Life\"], ''Alternative Law Journal''.</ref>\n\nDuring the juror selection process, both parties can object to up to three potential jurors without providing reasons.<ref>[http://www.lawlink.nsw.gov.au/lrc.nsf/pages/DP12CHP4 Discussion Paper 12 (1985) \u2013 Criminal Procedure: The Jury in a Criminal Trial] \u2014 Law Reform Commission \u2014 Lawlink NSW</ref>\n\nThe Office of the Sheriff of NSW disseminates resources for jurors.<ref>[http://www.courts.lawlink.nsw.gov.au/cats/jury_service.html Jury Service] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140530081056/http://www.courts.lawlink.nsw.gov.au/cats/jury_service.html |date=2014-05-30 }} \u2014 CaTS Corporate New South Wales</ref> Jurors may be compensated for their service.<ref>[http://www.courts.lawlink.nsw.gov.au/cats/jury_service/payment.html Payment for jury service] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140623164144/http://www.courts.lawlink.nsw.gov.au/cats/jury_service/payment.html |date=2014-06-23 }} \u2014 CaTS Corporate New South Wales</ref>\n\n==United Kingdom==\n{{Further|Juries in England and Wales}}\n{{Further|Trial by jury in Scotland}}\n\nAccording to 2016 figures from the [[Ministry of Justice]], there is about a 35% chance of people in England and Wales being summoned for jury service over the course of their lifetime. In Scotland the percentage is much higher due to having a lower population as well having juries made up of 15 people (as opposed to 12 people in England and Wales).<ref>{{cite news|title=What is the chance of being called for jury service?|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-36140259|publisher=BBC|date=17 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==United States==\n{{See also|Jury selection in the United States|Jury nullification in the United States|Taylor v. Louisiana}}\n\nWhen a person is called for porn duty in the [[United States]], that service is mandatory, and the person summoned for jury duty must attend. Failing to report for jury duty is illegal and results in a wide range of penalties, from simply being placed back into the selection pool to immediate criminal prosecution and having a [[Arrest_warrant#Bench_warrant|bench warrant]] issued for [[contempt of court]].<ref name=\"judiciary.state.nj.us\">{{cite web|url=http://www.judiciary.state.nj.us/juryreporting/juryfqa.pdf |title=Frequently Asked Questions About Juror Service in New Jersey |website=New Jersey Judiciary Court System |date=June 2017 |accessdate=2017-09-07}}</ref><ref name=\"https://www.cnn.com/2019/10/07/us/florida-juror-overslept-contempt-vacated-trnd/index.html\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/10/07/us/florida-juror-overslept-contempt-vacated-trnd/index.html |title=The judge who sentenced a man to 10 days in jail for oversleeping jury duty clears his record |website=CNN |date=October 2019 |accessdate=2019-10-10}}</ref>.  Employers are not allowed to fire an employee for being called to jury duty, but they are typically not required to pay salaries during this time.<ref name=\"judiciary.state.nj.us\"/> Jury duty reimbursement is as little as $5 per day, although a juror can plead to be excused for financial hardship.<ref name=\"https://www.nj.com/news/2011/07/rough_economy_makes_filling_nj.html\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nj.com/news/2011/07/rough_economy_makes_filling_nj.html |title=Rough economy makes filling N.J. juries more difficult, experts say |website=Star Ledger |date=July 2011 |accessdate=2019-10-06}}</ref>. A citizen who reports to jury duty may be asked to serve as a juror in a trial or as an alternate juror, or they may be dismissed.\n\nIn the United States, government employees are in a paid status of leave (in accordance with {{usc|5|6322}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://law.justia.com/codes/us/2010/title5/|title=Title 5: Government Organization and Employees \u2014 Justia|website=Law.justia.com |date= |accessdate=2012-02-14}}</ref>) for the duration spent serving as a juror (also known as court duty or court leave by some organizations). Many quasi-governmental organizations have adopted this provision into their contract manuals.<ref name=\"judiciary.state.nj.us\"/> Accordingly, government employees are in a paid status as long as they have received a summons in connection with a judicial proceeding, by a court or authority responsible for the conduct of that proceeding to serve as a juror (or witness) in the District of Columbia or a state, territory, or possession of the United States, [[Puerto Rico]], or the [[Trust Territory of the Pacific Islands]].\n\nThe [[Supreme Court of the United States]] has held, in ''[[Butler v. Perry]]'', [http://caselaw.lp.findlaw.com/scripts/getcase.pl?navby=case&court=us&vol=240&invol=328 240 U.S. 328] (1916), that the [[Thirteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Thirteenth Amendment]] does not prohibit \"enforcement of those duties which individuals owe to the state, such as services in the army, militia, on the jury, etc.\".\n\nIn both the United States and Canada, jurors having conscientious objection to service are generally excused from service. This chiefly includes religious groups such as the [[Amish]], [[Conservative Mennonites]], and [[Old Order Mennonites]].{{cn|date=September 2019}}\n\n==={{vanchor|Jury scam}} in the United States===\nIn recent years, US citizens have been targets of a \"jury scam\", wherein they are called by persons posing as officers from a court, claiming that the person did not show up for jury duty and that charges will be pressed. Potential victims of [[identity theft]] or [[identity fraud|fraud]], these targets are then told that the matter can be resolved if personal information is given. The [[US Department of Justice|Department of Justice]] recommends that recipients of these calls contact the court directly to avoid falling victim to this scam.<ref name=\"uscourts1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.uscourts.gov/FederalCourts/JuryService/JurorScams.aspx |title=Juror Scams |website=Uscourts.gov |date= |accessdate=2012-02-14}}</ref>\n\n[[United States federal courts|Federal courts]] mostly use the [[USPS]] (United States Postal Service) in their communications with prospective jurors, and any calls that are made will never ask for personal information.<ref name=\"uscourts1\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Wiktionary-inline}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jury Duty}}\n[[Category:Judiciaries]]\n[[Category:Criminal procedure]]\n[[Category:Juries]]\n[[Category:Local government]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses}}\n'''Jury duty''' or '''jury service''' is service as a [[jury|juror]] in a [[Legal proceedings|legal proceeding]].\n\n==Juror selection process==\n{{globalize|section|USA|date=April 2016}}\n{{Main|Jury selection}}\n\nThe [[prosecutor]] and [[Defense (legal)|defense]] can dismiss potential jurors for various reasons, which can vary from one state to another, and they can have a specific number of arbitrary dismissals, or unconditional [[peremptory challenge]], which does not require specific reasons. The judge can also dismiss potential jurors.\n\nSome courts had been sympathetic to jurors' privacy concerns and refer to jurors by number, and conduct ''[[voir dire]]'' ''[[in camera]]'' (i.e., in private). In the United States, there have also been [[Fifth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fifth Amendment]] challenges and medical privacy (e.g., [[HIPAA]]) objections to this.<ref>Hannaford P. L. (2001.) [http://contentdm.ncsconline.org/cgi-bin/showfile.exe?CISOROOT=/juries&CISOPTR=31 \"Making the Case for Juror Privacy: A New Framework for Court Policies and Procedures\"], State Justice Institute.</ref>\n\n[[File:Jury summons.jpg|thumb|A jury duty summons]]\n\n==Australia==\nAustralia uses an [[adversarial system]], and potential jurors are randomly selected from an [[electoral roll]].\n\nJurors receive a small payment for each day of attendance. Employers are also required to pay their employees \"make-up pay\", that is, the usual pay the employee would have earned from working, less the jury duty payment received from the state.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jury duty|url=https://www.fairwork.gov.au/leave/community-service-leave/jury-duty|website=[[Fair Work Ombudsman]]|publisher=[[Australian Government]]|accessdate=21 September 2017}}</ref> Under the [[National Employment Standards]], make-up pay is required only for the first ten days of jury service; however, the laws of Victoria, Queensland and Western Australia extend the make-up pay requirement for the entire duration of the jury service.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Nedim|first1=Ugur|title=What Does Jury Duty Pay?|url=https://www.sydneycriminallawyers.com.au/blog/what-does-jury-duty-pay/|website=Sydney Criminal Lawyers|accessdate=21 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n===New South Wales===\nThe jury system in New South Wales is administered by the Jury Services Branch of the Office of the Sheriff of New South Wales, an office in the [[Department of Attorney General and Justice (New South Wales)|New South Wales Department of Attorney General and Justice]], and operates in accordance with the ''Jury Act 1977''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legislation.nsw.gov.au/maintop/scanact/inforce/NONE/0 |title=NSW Legislation |publisher=Legislation.nsw.gov.au |date= |accessdate=2012-02-14}}</ref> and ''Jury Amendment Act 2010''. These laws detail persons who are disqualified, ineligible, or may be excused from jury service. In addition, the ''Jury Exemption Act 1965''<ref>[http://www.comlaw.gov.au/Series/C2004A07386 ''Jury Exemption Act 1965''] \u2014 ComLaw, Australian Government</ref><ref>{{Cite Legislation AU|Cth|act|jea1965203|Jury Exemption Act 1965}}</ref> and section 7, \"Excuse for cause\",<ref>[http://www.lawlink.nsw.gov.au/lawlink/lrc/ll_lrc.nsf/pages/LRC_r117chp07 Report 117 (2007) \u2013 Jury selection: 7. \"Excuse for cause\"] \u2014 Law Reform Commission \u2014 Lawlink NSW</ref> of LRC ''Report 117 (2007)'' details other persons who can or may not serve as jurors or otherwise claim exemption.<ref>[http://www.lawlink.nsw.gov.au/lawlink/lrc/ll_lrc.nsf/pages/LRC_r117toc  Report 117 (2007) \u2013 Jury selection] \u2014 Law Reform Commission \u2014 Lawlink NSW</ref>\n\nIndividuals who are blind and/or deaf may be excluded from jury service.<ref>McCallum R. (2011.) [http://www.altlj.org/news-and-views/opinion/92-participating-in-political-and-public-life \"Participating in Political and Public Life\"], ''Alternative Law Journal''.</ref>\n\nDuring the juror selection process, both parties can object to up to three potential jurors without providing reasons.<ref>[http://www.lawlink.nsw.gov.au/lrc.nsf/pages/DP12CHP4 Discussion Paper 12 (1985) \u2013 Criminal Procedure: The Jury in a Criminal Trial] \u2014 Law Reform Commission \u2014 Lawlink NSW</ref>\n\nThe Office of the Sheriff of NSW disseminates resources for jurors.<ref>[http://www.courts.lawlink.nsw.gov.au/cats/jury_service.html Jury Service] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140530081056/http://www.courts.lawlink.nsw.gov.au/cats/jury_service.html |date=2014-05-30 }} \u2014 CaTS Corporate New South Wales</ref> Jurors may be compensated for their service.<ref>[http://www.courts.lawlink.nsw.gov.au/cats/jury_service/payment.html Payment for jury service] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140623164144/http://www.courts.lawlink.nsw.gov.au/cats/jury_service/payment.html |date=2014-06-23 }} \u2014 CaTS Corporate New South Wales</ref>\n\n==United Kingdom==\n{{Further|Juries in England and Wales}}\n{{Further|Trial by jury in Scotland}}\n\nAccording to 2016 figures from the [[Ministry of Justice]], there is about a 35% chance of people in England and Wales being summoned for jury service over the course of their lifetime. In Scotland the percentage is much higher due to having a lower population as well having juries made up of 15 people (as opposed to 12 people in England and Wales).<ref>{{cite news|title=What is the chance of being called for jury service?|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-36140259|publisher=BBC|date=17 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==United States==\n{{See also|Jury selection in the United States|Jury nullification in the United States|Taylor v. Louisiana}}\n\nWhen a person is called for jury duty in the [[United States]], that service is mandatory, and the person summoned for jury duty must attend. Failing to report for jury duty is illegal and results in a wide range of penalties, from simply being placed back into the selection pool to immediate criminal prosecution and having a [[Arrest_warrant#Bench_warrant|bench warrant]] issued for [[contempt of court]].<ref name=\"judiciary.state.nj.us\">{{cite web|url=http://www.judiciary.state.nj.us/juryreporting/juryfqa.pdf |title=Frequently Asked Questions About Juror Service in New Jersey |website=New Jersey Judiciary Court System |date=June 2017 |accessdate=2017-09-07}}</ref><ref name=\"https://www.cnn.com/2019/10/07/us/florida-juror-overslept-contempt-vacated-trnd/index.html\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/10/07/us/florida-juror-overslept-contempt-vacated-trnd/index.html |title=The judge who sentenced a man to 10 days in jail for oversleeping jury duty clears his record |website=CNN |date=October 2019 |accessdate=2019-10-10}}</ref>.  Employers are not allowed to fire an employee for being called to jury duty, but they are typically not required to pay salaries during this time.<ref name=\"judiciary.state.nj.us\"/> Jury duty reimbursement is as little as $5 per day, although a juror can plead to be excused for financial hardship.<ref name=\"https://www.nj.com/news/2011/07/rough_economy_makes_filling_nj.html\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nj.com/news/2011/07/rough_economy_makes_filling_nj.html |title=Rough economy makes filling N.J. juries more difficult, experts say |website=Star Ledger |date=July 2011 |accessdate=2019-10-06}}</ref>. A citizen who reports to jury duty may be asked to serve as a juror in a trial or as an alternate juror, or they may be dismissed.\n\nIn the United States, government employees are in a paid status of leave (in accordance with {{usc|5|6322}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://law.justia.com/codes/us/2010/title5/|title=Title 5: Government Organization and Employees \u2014 Justia|website=Law.justia.com |date= |accessdate=2012-02-14}}</ref>) for the duration spent serving as a juror (also known as court duty or court leave by some organizations). Many quasi-governmental organizations have adopted this provision into their contract manuals.<ref name=\"judiciary.state.nj.us\"/> Accordingly, government employees are in a paid status as long as they have received a summons in connection with a judicial proceeding, by a court or authority responsible for the conduct of that proceeding to serve as a juror (or witness) in the District of Columbia or a state, territory, or possession of the United States, [[Puerto Rico]], or the [[Trust Territory of the Pacific Islands]].\n\nThe [[Supreme Court of the United States]] has held, in ''[[Butler v. Perry]]'', [http://caselaw.lp.findlaw.com/scripts/getcase.pl?navby=case&court=us&vol=240&invol=328 240 U.S. 328] (1916), that the [[Thirteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Thirteenth Amendment]] does not prohibit \"enforcement of those duties which individuals owe to the state, such as services in the army, militia, on the jury, etc.\".\n\nIn both the United States and Canada, jurors having conscientious objection to service are generally excused from service. This chiefly includes religious groups such as the [[Amish]], [[Conservative Mennonites]], and [[Old Order Mennonites]].{{cn|date=September 2019}}\n\n==={{vanchor|Jury scam}} in the United States===\nIn recent years, US citizens have been targets of a \"jury scam\", wherein they are called by persons posing as officers from a court, claiming that the person did not show up for jury duty and that charges will be pressed. Potential victims of [[identity theft]] or [[identity fraud|fraud]], these targets are then told that the matter can be resolved if personal information is given. The [[US Department of Justice|Department of Justice]] recommends that recipients of these calls contact the court directly to avoid falling victim to this scam.<ref name=\"uscourts1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.uscourts.gov/FederalCourts/JuryService/JurorScams.aspx |title=Juror Scams |website=Uscourts.gov |date= |accessdate=2012-02-14}}</ref>\n\n[[United States federal courts|Federal courts]] mostly use the [[USPS]] (United States Postal Service) in their communications with prospective jurors, and any calls that are made will never ask for personal information.<ref name=\"uscourts1\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Wiktionary-inline}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jury Duty}}\n[[Category:Judiciaries]]\n[[Category:Criminal procedure]]\n[[Category:Juries]]\n[[Category:Local government]]\n", "name_user": "76.182.247.70", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eUnited States)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jury_duty"}
{"title_page": "SmileML", "text_new": "{{db-spam|help=off}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name                = SmileML, Inc.\n| logo                = \n| type                = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| industry            = Software\n| founded             = {{Start date and age|2017|12|17}}\n| founder             = {{Unbulleted list|Ethan Petersen|Shannon Anderson|}}\n| hq_location_city    = [[Boston, Massachusetts]]\n| hq_location_country = [[United States]]\n| products            = {{URL|salespot.io|SaleSpot}}\n| website             = {{URL|smile-ml.com}}\n}}\nSmileML, Inc., commonly known as smileML, is a software development company specializing in [[Edge computing|edge-based]] [[emotion recognition]] and [[:simple:Machine_learning|machine learning]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smile-ml.com/|title=smileML {{!}} Making Emotion Recognition an Exact Science|website=www.smile-ml.com|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> SmileML has developed camera-agnostic technology that analyzes facial expressions and gait to interpret the emotional state of an individual.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smile-ml.com/technology|title=smileML {{!}} Technology|website=www.smile-ml.com|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> Commercially, SmileML's technology is being used in its sales analytics tool, [https://www.salespot.io/ SaleSpot], to analyze sentiment and body language during sales video calls to provide real-time coaching and identify winning strategies.\n\n== History ==\nSmileML was inspired by the founders' experience developing [[:simple:IOS|iOS apps]]. While conducting [[user research]] before launching an app, they came up with the idea to use emotion recognition during user research interviews to get a better understanding of how people feel about consumer products and websites.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://edu.google.com/why-google/case-studies/smileml/|title=Case Studies: SmileML|last=|first=|date=|website=Google for Education|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-03|dead-url=}}</ref> In 2019, SmileML completed with [http://techstars.blog/content/accelerators/air-force-accelerator-powered-techstars-proudly-announces-class-2019/ Techstars Air Force Accelerator] where it began expanding its technology offerings into the sales industry with its product [https://www.salespot.io/ SaleSpot].\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External Links ==\n\n* [https://www.smile-ml.com/ Official Website]\n", "text_old": "{{db-spam|help=off}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name                = SmileML, Inc.\n| logo                = \n| type                = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| industry            = Software\n| founded             = {{Start date and age|2017|12|17}}\n| founder             = {{Unbulleted list|Ethan Petersen|Shannon Anderson|}}\n| hq_location_city    = [[Boston, Massachusetts]]\n| hq_location_country = [[United States]]\n| products            = {{URL|salespot.io|SaleSpot}}\n| website             = {{URL|smile-ml.com}}\n}}\nSmileML, Inc., commonly known as smileML, is a software development company specializing in [[Edge computing|edge-based]] [[emotion recognition]] and [[:simple:Machine_learning|machine learning]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smile-ml.com/|title=smileML {{!}} Making Emotion Recognition an Exact Science|website=www.smile-ml.com|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> SmileML has developed camera-agnostic technology that analyzes facial expressions and gait to interpret the emotional state of an individual.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smile-ml.com/technology|title=smileML {{!}} Technology|website=www.smile-ml.com|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> Commercially, SmileML's technology is being used in its sales analytics tool, [https://www.salespot.io/ SaleSpot], to analyze sentiment and body language during sales video calls to provide real-time coaching and identify winning strategies.\n\n== History ==\nSmileML was inspired by the founders' experience developing [[:simple:IOS|iOS apps]]. While conducting [[user research]] before launching an app, they came up with the idea to use emotion recognition during user research interviews to get a better understanding of how people feel about consumer products and websites.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://edu.google.com/why-google/case-studies/smileml/|title=Case Studies: SmileML|last=|first=|date=|website=Google for Education|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-03|dead-url=}}</ref> In 2019, SmileML completed with [http://techstars.blog/content/accelerators/air-force-accelerator-powered-techstars-proudly-announces-class-2019/ Techstars Air Force Accelerator] where it began expanding its technology offerings into the sales industry with its product [https://www.salespot.io/ SaleSpot].\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External Links ==\n\n* [https://www.smile-ml.com/ Official Website]\n* [https://www.salespot.io/ SaleSpot]\n", "name_user": "Shanxanderson", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removed something that looked like it could have been promotional for my speedy deletion contest.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SmileML"}
